---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Adrien Brault-Lesage"
  description="Adrien Brault-Lesage - software engineer based near Paris, Founding Engineer at Sluicebox.ai."
>
  <article class="prose max-w-none">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-8">Hey, I'm Adrien</h1>

    <p class="text-lg mb-6">
      Software engineer based near Paris, France. I love building things, learning, and solving
      problems - software engineering is the perfect playground for that. Over time I've
      become just as obsessed with outcomes as with the craft itself: what matters most,
      how fast you can learn, and how to get there with less.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      I've spent most of my career working remotely from France for US companies.
      Currently Founding Engineer at{" "}
      <a href="https://sluicebox.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Sluicebox.ai</a>,
      making it faster and more accurate to assess the environmental impact of electronic
      products. It's a genuinely hard problem space, which makes it a great place to push
      what AI can actually do in practice.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Open source</h2>
    <p class="mb-6">
      Open source has always been a big part of how I learn and work. I started deep in
      the PHP/Symfony ecosystem - built libraries, contributed upstream, created the{" "}
      <a href="https://plugins.jetbrains.com/plugin/7219-symfony-support" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IntelliJ Symfony Plugin</a>{" "}
      (8M+ downloads, now maintained by Haehnchen). These days I'm in different ecosystems,
      but the instinct is the same: learn from others, and share whenever I can.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">How I work</h2>
    <p class="mb-6">
      A lot of what matters to me in engineering comes back to simplicity and feedback.
      Most complexity isn't inevitable - it's a design choice that wasn't questioned. And
      the speed of a team really comes down to the speed of its feedback loops. That's a
      big part of why AI is so interesting to me right now - not just because it speeds
      things up, but because it keeps changing how I think, learn, and build.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">What I'm into</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Home automation</strong> - Home Assistant, Zigbee, ESPHome
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>3D printing</strong> - mostly functional parts, plus a few designs on <a href="https://www.printables.com/@AdrienBrault_1580788" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Printables</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Photography</strong>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Self-hosting</strong>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
